<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        NPC Event Points
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Create NPC / Create Enemy, Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy, and Enemy Flags Event Points.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Overview
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        NPC Event Points are used to create and control non-playable characters in a mission. This
        includes police, enemies, civilians, gang members, named characters, and special AI-driven
        actors.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        There are three closely related Event Point types that should not be confused:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Create NPC / Create Enemy</Bold> — creates or spawns a new NPC into the mission.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy</Bold> — modifies an existing NPC’s properties later,
                such as movement or AI behaviour. It requires a <Bold>Target EP</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
        <ListItem>
            <Paragraph>
                <Bold>Enemy Flags</Bold> — modifies only the behaviour/zone/restriction flags of an
                existing NPC. This is required when you need to change flags such as Guilty, Fake Wander,
                Can Carry, Invulnerable, zone restrictions, and similar flag values. It also requires
                a <Bold>Target EP</Bold>.
            </Paragraph>
        </ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_npc_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical distinction:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy does not change the behaviour flag mask.
                    If you need to change flags such as Guilty, Fake Wander, Can Carry, Invulnerable,
                    zone restrictions, or other behaviour flags, use the separate Enemy Flags Event Point.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Suggested Grouping
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        NPC Event Points can quickly become hard to manage, so it helps to use consistent letter and
        colour groups. This is not mandatory, but it makes large missions much easier to debug.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Group C / Blue</Bold> — police officers.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Group C / Red</Bold> — enemies or hostile gang members.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Group C / White</Bold> — civilians.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        These groupings are only examples. You can use any grouping scheme that keeps your mission
        readable.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_npc_grouping_example.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Create NPC / Create Enemy
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Create NPC / Create Enemy</Bold> spawns a new NPC into the mission. This is the Event
        Point used when you want to place a police officer, civilian, enemy, gang member, named
        character, or similar actor.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Example: Adding Two Police Officers
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        In this example, two police officers are added in <Bold>Group C</Bold> with the colour
        <Bold>Blue</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select <Bold>Create NPC</Bold> or <Bold>Create Enemy</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the letter group to <Bold>C</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the colour to <Bold>Blue</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the NPC type to <Bold>Cop</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Place the first police officer on the map.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select the created officer and press <Bold>Ctrl+C</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Move the cursor to the desired second position and press <Bold>Ctrl+V</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Rotate each officer using the orange direction handle so they face the intended target, such as a Baalrog.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Copying and pasting an Event Point preserves the colour and letter grouping. This makes it
        faster to duplicate similar NPCs without repeatedly setting their group data.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_npc_two_cops_example.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Create NPC Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Double-click a Create NPC / Create Enemy Event Point to edit it. The type-specific
        properties determine who the NPC is, how much health they have, how they move, what AI
        behaviour they use, what weapons they carry, and what item they may drop when searched.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_npc_edit_window.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        NPC Type
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Type</Bold> field controls what kind of character is spawned. Available types
        include civilians, police, gang members, named characters, and variations with starting
        weapons.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Civilian</Bold> and <Bold>Civilian With Balloon</Bold> — these appear to behave the same.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Woman</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Fat Woman</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Workman with Green Overalls</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Black Gang Member</Bold> — clothing colour can change depending on the Event Point number.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>White Gang Member</Bold> variants, including Bish and McClean.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Gordansky</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Old Man in Leather Jacket</Bold> / Wild Bill.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>MIB</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Darci</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Roper</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Various versions of these types with starting weapons.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Count
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Count</Bold> field is available for editing, but testing suggests that only one
        NPC spawns per Event Point regardless of the count entered. To spawn multiple NPCs, create
        or copy multiple Event Points.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Health
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Health</Bold> value controls the amount of health the NPC has.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Starting Weapons
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Starting Weapons define the weapons that the NPC has in their possession when spawned.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Item Drops
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Item Drops define what can be found when the NPC is searched after being arrested or killed.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#3A2A2A" BorderBrush="#7A4A4A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0A0A0">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Important:</Run>
                <Run>
                    NPC Count appears editable but generally only one character spawns per Event Point.
                    Use copy/paste for multiple NPCs.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Adjust NPC</Bold> or <Bold>Adjust Enemy</Bold> modifies an NPC that already exists in
        the mission. It does not spawn a new NPC. It targets an existing Create NPC / Create Enemy
        Event Point and changes that NPC later.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Use Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy when you need to change non-flag properties such as movement,
        AI type, target references, follow behaviour, guard target, or similar NPC behaviour fields.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical required field:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy must have Target EP set.
                    Target EP must be the Event Point number of the existing NPC you want to change.
                    For example, if the NPC is Event Point 12, set Target EP to 12.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_adjust_npc_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Target EP: The NPC Being Adjusted
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Target EP</Bold> tells the game which existing NPC should be modified. This must be the
        <Bold>Event Point number</Bold> of the NPC created by Create NPC / Create Enemy.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
Example:
Create NPC is Event Point 12.
Adjust NPC must use Target EP = 12.
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        Target EP does <Bold>not</Bold> mean the Adjust NPC Event Point’s own index number. It means
        the index number of the NPC being changed.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        If Target EP points to the wrong Event Point, the wrong NPC may be adjusted, or the
        adjustment may appear to do nothing.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_adjust_npc_target_ep.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        What Adjust NPC Does Not Do
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy does not change the NPC flag mask.</Bold> This means it is
        not the correct Event Point for changing behaviour flags such as:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Lazy.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Diligent.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Gang.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Fight Back.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Just Kill Player.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Robotic.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Restricted Movement.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Only Player Kills.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Blue/Cyan/Yellow/Magenta zone flags.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Invulnerable.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Guilty.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Fake Wander.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Can Carry.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        To change those flags after the NPC has spawned, use the separate <Bold>Enemy Flags</Bold>
        Event Point.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="26" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Enemy Flags Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Enemy Flags</Bold> is a separate Event Point used to adjust the behaviour flag mask of
        an existing NPC. It is similar to Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy in that it targets an existing
        NPC, but it is more specific: it only changes flags.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Use Enemy Flags when you need to change behaviour flags, zone restrictions, or other flag
        values after the NPC has already spawned.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical required field:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Enemy Flags must have Target EP set.
                    Target EP must be the Event Point number of the existing NPC whose flags you want to change.
                    Enemy Flags does not create a new NPC.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_enemy_flags_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Enemy Flags Target EP
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Enemy Flags must point to the NPC being modified. For example:
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
Example:
Create Enemy is Event Point 22.
Enemy Flags must use Target EP = 22.
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph>
        Do not put the Enemy Flags Event Point’s own number into Target EP unless that number is
        actually the NPC being modified. In normal use, Target EP is the number of the existing NPC
        created by Create NPC / Create Enemy.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_enemy_flags_target_ep.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        When to Use Adjust NPC vs Enemy Flags
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#555" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <StackPanel>
                <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" Margin="0,0,0,6">
                    <Run FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#9FE3A6">Use Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy when changing:</Run>
                </TextBlock>
                <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" Margin="16,0,0,10">
                    Movement type, AI type, follow target, guard target, target references, or similar non-flag NPC properties.
                </TextBlock>
                <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" Margin="0,0,0,6">
                    <Run FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#9FE3A6">Use Enemy Flags when changing:</Run>
                </TextBlock>
                <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" Margin="16,0,0,0">
                    Behaviour flags, zone flags, Guilty, Fake Wander, Can Carry, Invulnerable, Restricted Movement, Only Player Kills, or similar flag-mask values.
                </TextBlock>
            </StackPanel>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Example: Change an NPC’s Flags Later
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        This example changes an existing NPC so that a flag-based behaviour is applied later in the
        mission.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create an NPC using <Bold>Create NPC / Create Enemy</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Note the NPC’s Event Point number from the Event Points list. For example, it may be <Bold>Event Point 22</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Add a new Event Point and choose <Bold>Enemy Flags</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Target EP</Bold> to <Bold>22</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the flags you want to apply, such as <Bold>Guilty</Bold>, <Bold>Can Carry</Bold>, <Bold>Fake Wander</Bold>, or <Bold>Invulnerable</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose the trigger that should apply the flag change, such as <Bold>Dependency</Bold>, <Bold>Player Enters Radius</Bold>, or <Bold>Timer</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Save and test the mission to confirm the correct NPC receives the flag change.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>
    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#666" Margin="0,18,0,14"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

<Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Movement, AI Types, and Flags Reference
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Reference for NPC movement modes, AI types, AI targets, behaviour flags, zone flags, Adjust NPC, and Enemy Flags.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        Movement Modes
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Movement controls how the NPC moves after it spawns. These movement-style settings are also
        useful when working with <Bold>Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy</Bold>, because Adjust NPC can be
        used to change an existing NPC’s movement later in the mission.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_npc_movement_settings.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Stand Still</Bold> — the NPC does not move.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Patrol Waypoints In Order</Bold> — patrols each subsequent Simple Waypoint Event Point within the same colour and letter group, in numerical order.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Patrol Waypoints Randomly</Bold> — patrols waypoints in the same colour and letter group, but in random order.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Wander</Bold> — wanders around the map aimlessly, similar to civilians, except into No Wander Zones.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Follow</Bold> — follows the Event Point specified in the Follow EP box.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Warm Hands</Bold> — appears unused; likely intended for warming hands near fire.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Follow On See</Bold> — follows the Follow EP target only once that target is in visual range.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Hands Up</Bold> — character has hands in the air; works best with AI Type not set to None and with certain AI types such as Civilian or Cop.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Tied Up</Bold> — appears to behave the same as Hands Up.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        AI Types
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        AI Type controls the character’s high-level behaviour. This is separate from movement.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_npc_ai_type_settings.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Civilian</Bold> — acts as an innocent civilian.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Cop</Bold> — targets enemies that attack you; only cops can arrest.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Violent Youth</Bold> — actively targets the player if they see you.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Guard a Door</Bold> — no obvious current effect; likely old door-guarding behaviour.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Driver</Bold> — enters the nearest available vehicle.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Bomb Disposer</Bold> — unused.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Biker</Bold> — unused.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Fight Test Dummy</Bold> — tutorial fight dummy; used with combat ability settings.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Bully</Bold> — actively targets the player.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Cop Driver</Bold> — driver behaviour for police vehicles.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Suicide</Bold> — immediately dies on spawn.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Flee Player</Bold> — flees once the player is in sight.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Group Genocide</Bold> — unused.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>MIB</Bold> — attacks the player on sight.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Summoner</Bold> — bright white orb appears and the NPC floats upward; likely beta Bane-related behaviour.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Hypochondriac</Bold> — alive but passed out.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Shoot Dead Assassin</Bold> — if armed, targets the Guard EP with unlimited fire until the target is dead, then wanders.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        AI Target Fields
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Some AI behaviours use Event Point references. These references must point to the correct
        Event Point number or the behaviour will not affect the intended target.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Guard EP</Bold> — used for targeting or guard-related behaviour.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Follow EP</Bold> — used by Follow and Follow On See movement modes.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Target EP for Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy</Bold> — must be the Event Point number of the existing NPC being modified.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Target EP for Enemy Flags</Bold> — must be the Event Point number of the existing NPC whose flags are being modified.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Target EP warning:</Run>
                <Run>
                    For both Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy and Enemy Flags, Target EP must correspond to the NPC’s Event Point number.
                    It is the target NPC, not the adjusting event’s own number.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Behaviour and Zone Flags
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Behaviour flags modify how the NPC behaves. They can be set when the NPC is created or
        changed later using the <Bold>Enemy Flags</Bold> Event Point. <Bold>Adjust NPC / Adjust Enemy
        does not change these flags.</Bold>
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_npc_flags_panel.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Lazy — Bit 0</Bold> — makes the enemy less alert or reactive.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Diligent — Bit 1</Bold> — opposite of Lazy; more alert or persistent. Original string is misspelled as Dilligent.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Gang — Bit 2</Bold> — marks the person as part of a gang or faction.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Fight Back — Bit 3</Bold> — allows the person to fight back when attacked.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Just Kill Player — Bit 4</Bold> — forces hostile intent toward the player specifically.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Robotic — Bit 5</Bold> — makes behaviour more scripted or rigid.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Restricted Movement — Bit 6</Bold> — limits movement, probably within an area, route, or navigation zone.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Only Player Kills — Bit 7</Bold> — only player kills count or are allowed for the NPC.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Blue Zone — Bit 8</Bold> — zone-related flag.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Cyan Zone — Bit 9</Bold> — zone-related flag.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Yellow Zone — Bit 10</Bold> — zone-related flag.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Magenta Zone — Bit 11</Bold> — zone-related flag.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Invulnerable — Bit 12</Bold> — prevents lethal damage.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Guilty — Bit 13</Bold> — marks the person as guilty or criminal.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Fake Wander — Bit 14</Bold> — makes the person appear to wander using simplified/faked wandering.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Can Carry — Bit 15</Bold> — allows the person to be carried.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>
</FlowDocument>
